export const notes = {
  "VAFA": "Vanity Fair first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1919 and continued to submit regularly through the end of 1935, at which point it was purchased by and combined with Vogue.",
  "THGR": "The Thrilling Group first submitted data to the ABC under the title Thrilling Fiction Unit for the period July-December 1935 and continued to submit consistently through the end of 1957 under this title (July 1935-June 1937), Thrilling Group (July 1937-June 1946), and Thrilling Fiction Group (July 1946-December 1957). Between July 1943 and December 1950 all geographical breakdowns were reported as single copy sales.",
  "SUPE": "The comic Superman submitted individual reports from July 1945-June 1947. Before and after this period it was included in the National Comics Group (1943-1945, 1947-1972).",
  "STSM": "Street and Smith Combination first submitted reports to the ABC in 1919. Beginning in July 1941 it followed competitors’ practices of including the circulation of all weekly and biweekly magazines instead of one per month, resulting in a perceived spike in circulation.",
  "SMSE": "The Smart Set initially submitted data in a combined report with Black Mask for the period July-December 1922 but submitted an individual report beginning with the January-June 1923 period. It submitted reports consistently through June 1930. Before 1924 it submitted no geographical breakdowns, for the period January-June 1924 it submitted geographical breakdowns of subscription sales only, and after this it submitted complete geographical breakdowns. No detail is given for the magazine’s spike in circulation in late 1924, though the magazine changed ownership and format around this time.",
  "SHST": "Short Stories first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1919 and submitted irregularly during its association with the ABC. It submitted consistently through June 1932, but its July-December 1932 report was stamped “Statement Not Received.” It was not included in the ABC from January 1933 through June 1934, but then submitted regularly from January 1935 through December 1940. After this, most of its reports through the final submission (December 1951) were marked “Statement Not Received,” though a few stray reports were submitted during this time (July-December 1942, July-December 1943, July-December 1944, and July-December 1950). At various points, geographical circulation data was combined in a joint report with Frontier (January 1926-June 1929), West (July-December 1935), and Weird Tales (July 1939-December 1950). Geographical breakdowns before 1928 included subscription sales only.",
  "SCMA": "Scribner’s Magazine first submitted reports to the ABC in the period January-June 1919 and submitted regularly through the end of 1938. Its January-June 1939 report was marked “Statement in Correspondence.” Before 1923 its geographical breakdowns mostly included only subscription sales, with two exceptions: July-December 1919 and July-December 1921.",
  "SAEV": "The Saturday Evening Post first submitted reports to the ABC for the period January-June 1919 and submitted regularly through its final issue in early 1969. Issue circulation for July-December 1956 was taken from a very faint microfilm at the AAM, and this data may not be entirely accurate. No geographical data was reported in the final report covering January and February 1969.",
  "POPU": "Popular Publications first submitted its group report to the ABC for the period January-June 1935 and continued to submit regularly through the end of 1953. For brief periods, it used other reporting titles: Popular Publications Master Group (1938) and Popular Fiction Group (1947-1953).",
  "PLAY": "Playboy first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1955 and submitted consistently through the end of 1972.",
  "NEYO": "The New Yorker first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1925 and continued to submit regularly through the end of 1972. During one reporting period (January-June 1970) circulation information was not submitted in time for inclusion in the ABC Blue Book. Before July 1927 geographical breakdowns include only subscription sales.",
  "MUNS": "The Munsey Combination first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1926 and submitted regularly through the end of 1942. From July 1941 to December 1942, it submitted under the title Munsey Special Combination, after it acquired a number of new titles. Before 1928 geographical breakdowns include only subscription sales. Beginning in July 1941 it followed competitors’ practices of including the circulation of all weekly and biweekly magazines instead of one per month, resulting in a perceived spike in circulation.",
  "LIBE": "Liberty first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1924 and submitted complete circulation information through the end of 1949. Between July 1935 and December 1946 reports featured the title Liberty (Including Canada) or Liberty (Including Canadian Edition). Between July 1941 and December 1946, the magazine submitted a separate report under the title Liberty (U.S.), which featured the same geographical breakdown with no Canadian circulation reported. Here we have used the more complete “Including Canada” reports through 1946, after which the Canadian edition was reported independently.",
  "JUDG": "Judge first submitted data to the ABC for the period of January-June 1919 and submitted through the middle of 1938. The report for January-June 1922, available only on microfilm at the Alliance for Audited Media, has circulation information for three issues obscured, and the report from July-December 1926 is marked “Statement Not Received.” One issue from 1925 (November 7) was denied mailing privileges and no circulation figure was reported for newsstand sales. Between 1921 and 1928, geographical data represents only subscription sales, with one exception (July-December 1921).",
  "HARP": "Harper’s first submitted data to the ABC in the period January-June 1919 and continued to submit regularly through 1972, failing to submit formal reports only twice: the period January-June 1924, when the report was marked “Statement Not Received,” and January-June 1928, when the report was marked “Statement in Correspondence.” Geographical breakdowns before 1928 included only subscription sales.",
  "FORU": "The Forum first submitted reports to the ABC for the period January-June 1925. Before 1928, geographical breakdowns were only submitted for subscription sales. In 1930 it acquired the Century and became Forum and Century, which is also represented here.",
  "FIHO": "The pulp publisher Fiction House first submitted reports to the ABC for the period July-December 1924 in a report combining titles Action Stories (previously reported as a single title) and Novelets. It continued to submit circulation data regularly, reporting under a string of growing house titles through the end of 1929. From January 1930 through June 1931 its reports featured the title Fiction House. Geographical data before 1928 includes only mail subscriptions.",
  "DIAL": "The Dial submitted first submitted reports to the ABC for the period July-December 1921 and continued to submit through the end of 1923. As was true for many small circulation magazines, the Dial only submitted geographical breakdowns of subscription sales.",
  "DEFI": "The Dell Fiction Group includes reports submitted to the ABC under a number of different titles: Dell Men’s Group, Dell Fiction Group, and Dell Men’s List. These reports generally feature the same titles over time. The Dell Men’s Group reported first submitted in the period July-December 1929, but these titles were all individually reported. Circulation data was first combined from January-December 1930 (though some titles were still individual reported in this period), and, after a period when it was not included in the ABC, the group submitted circulation data from July 1934 through April 1943. Before 1940 all circulation reported was designated as single copy or newsstand sales.",
  "COLL": "Collier’s first submitted reports to the ABC for the period January-June 1919 and reported consistently through its final issue in early 1957. The printers’ strike disrupted publication in 1919 and 1920, as noted in the reports. From July 1919 through December 1922 the magazine submitted geographical breakdown of only subscription sales.",
  "CLMAB": "Clayton Magazines began submitting reports of bimonthly magazines to the ABC for July-December 1927 and continued to submit through the end of 1930, at which point these titles were incorporated into the Clayton Magazines monthly group. Both biannual 1930 reports however, were stamped “Report in Correspondence.” The reports never featured the title “Clayton Magazines,” instead using a string of included titles usually foregrounding Ace High and Ranch Romances. Prior to 1928, the reports offered no geographical breakdown for circulation.",
  "CLMA": "Clayton Magazines first submitted reports on monthly titles to the ABC for January-June 1926, and continued to submit through the end of 1932. The composition of this group changed significantly over time, and it was not officially designated the Clayton Magazines group in the reports until 1931. Reports frequently broke out circulation for certain titles, which have been noted here. Prior to 1928, the reports offered no geographical breakdown for circulation.",
  "CENT": "The Century first submitted reports to the ABC for the January-June 1919 period and reported consistently through the end of 1929, at which point it was purchased by the Forum and combined under the title Forum and Century. Circulation of this combination can be found under the Forum. Before 1928, the Century submitted geographical breakdowns only for subscription sales.",
  "BLMA": "Black Mask first submitted data to the ABC in 1923. In this year it was reported in a combination with Smart Set, and in 1924 and 1925 it was reported in a combination with Saucy Stories/Heart to Heart. Black Mask was first reported by itself in January 1926. It did not submit any geographical breakdowns of circulation until submitting a breakdown of only single copy sales in January-June 1928. After this it reported all geographical data. Beginning in July 1935 its geographical data was combined with Ranch Romances, and it joined the Popular Publications group in 1940.",
  "BLBO": "Blue Book Magazine first submitted reports to the ABC for the January-June 1922 period, and it submitted reports consistently through June 1941. It submitted complete geographical breakdowns throughout its entire membership in the ABC.",
  "BATM": "The comic Batman submitted individual reports from July 1945-June 1947. Before and after this period it was included in the National Comics Group (1943-1945, 1947-1972).",
  "ATMO": "The Atlantic Monthly first submitted reports to the ABC for January-June 1919 and continued to submit reports regularly through end of 1972. Some early reports (January-June 1919, January-December 1925) feature geographical breakdowns for only mail subscriptions; otherwise the data is complete.",
  "AMME": "The American Mercury first submitted reports to the ABC for July-December 1924. From July 1928-June 1930, reports noted “Statement Not Received,” and the July-December 1931 report was stamped “Statement in Correspondence.” The magazine’s later reports also were somewhat irregular; it was not included in the ABC Blue Book in the July-December 1950 volume, and from July 1951-June 1952 reports were marked “Statement Not Received.” Geographical data before July 1926 features information from subscriptions only.",
  "AMMA": "The American Magazine first submitted reports to the ABC for January-June 1919 and submitted data regularly through June 1956; its January-June 1925 report, for which our data is missing, notes “Statement in Correspondence.”",
  "ADVE": "Adventure first submitted reports to the ABC for January-June 1919 and reported consistently through June 1935, after which it was purchased by Popular Publications and began showing up in that group in January 1936. With a few exceptions, before 1924 Adventure submitted a geographical breakdown of only subscription sales.",
  "4MCO": "4-Most Comics first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1945 and submitted through the end of 1948. All circulation for this title was reported as single copy sales. Geographical breakdowns were not included in its final report (July-December 1948).",
  "ACDE": "Actual Detective Stories first submitted data (under the title Actual Detective Stories of Women in Crime) for the period January-June 1938 and continued to submit through the the end of 1940. The title was shortened in the reports to Actual Detective Stories beginning in 1940.",
  "ACFI": "Ace Fiction Group Joined the ABC in 1936 and submitted its first complete report for July-December 1936. A pulp magazine group, it included a number of titles during its membership in the ABC, which concluded at the end of 1949.",
  "ACHI": "Ace High first submitted reports to the ABC for July-December of 1922. Over its lifetime, it shifted from a monthly to a bimonthly and back. From July 1927-December 1929 it was included in the Clayton Magazines bimonthly group, and from July 1930 to December 1932 it was included in the Clayton Magazines monthly group. It was part of the Dell Fiction Group from July 1934-June 1935 and it joined (as Ace High Western) the Popular Publications group in 1936. Reports from 1922-1927 include very little geographical breakdown (as was permitted for magazines under a certain circulation). Geographical data from 1930 includes the entire Clayton Magazines bimonthly group.",
  "ACST": "Action Stories first submitted reports for July-December 1922, joining the Fiction House group in July 1924. It re-entered the ABC Blue Books as a single title beginning in 1935, but submitted data irregularly after June 1938 (with many reports noting “Statement Not Received”). Reports in 1923 and 1924 feature geographical breakdowns for subscriptions only (a very small fraction of total sales).",
  "ALAM": "The All American Comics Group first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1941 and submitted through the end of 1943. The January-June 1944 report was marked “Membership Cancelled.” All circulation was reported as single copy sales.",
  "ALFI": "All Fiction was a Dell Publications title that reported its own issue circulation and geographical breakdown for one reporting period (July-December 1930). Otherwise, it was included in the Dell Fiction Group.",
  "AMCO": "The American Comics Group submitted aggregate data to the ABC under a number of titles beginning with the January-June 1948 report and continuing through the end of 1954. These additional titles included American Comic Group; American Comics Group (Combined Romance Unit and Youth Unit); and American Comics Group, Combined Unit A and Unit B. All circulation was reported as single copy sales.",
  "AMFI": "The American Fiction Group was a pulp publishing group that submitted reports to the ABC irregularly from 1937-1942. Gaps in the data were represented by reports noting “Statement Not Received”; a Blue Book report from July-December 1943 notes “Membership Cancelled.”",
  "AMST": "Amazing Stories first reported individual circulation data as a part of the Teck Publications Group for the period July-December 1936. After its purchase by Ziff-Davis, it submitted individual reports from January 1938-June 1939 before being incorporated into the Ziff-Davis Group. Geographical breakdowns from 1936 and 1937 include the entire Teck Publications Group.",
  "ARAL": "First submitting reports for January-June 1919, the Argosy Combination included Argosy and All-Story Weekly magazines. In July 1920, these two magazines merged to become the Argosy All-Story Weekly. Reports were submitted regularly through the end of 1925 before they joined a new iteration of the Argosy Combination (with Munsey’s Magazine) in 1925 and the Munsey Combination (adding Flynn’s) in 1926. The geographical breakdowns submitted for this title included only mail subscriptions.",
  "ARCO": "The Argosy Combination (the second version of this combination) united the Argosy All-Story Weekly and Munsey’s Magazine and submitted reports to the ABC in 1925 before adding Flynn’s and becoming the Munsey Combination in 1926. Geographical breakdowns include only mail subscriptions.",
  "BRST": "Breezy Stories was initially included in a publishing group with Young’s Magazine (and, from July 1923-June 1927, Droll Stories), but when it merged with Young’s in October 1933 it began to submit individual data to the ABC. It submitted circulation through the end of 1937 but reports in 1938 read “Release Delayed Because of Non-Compliance With Bylaws and Rules” and reports in 1939 noted merely “Statement Not Received” before the January-June 1940 report declared that the magazine had been “Dropped from Membership.”",
  "CAMA": "The comic Captain Marvel Adventures submitted individual reports to the ABC from January 1944 through December 1946. It was included in the Fawcett Comic Group in reports submitted before and after this (1943, 1947-1952).",
  "COHU": "College Humor first submitted reports to the ABC for the period July-December 1923 and submitted reports irregularly through the middle of 1940. Submissions from July-December 1932 and July-December 1933 were marked “Statement Not Received” and the magazine was not included in the ABC Blue Books from January 1934 through June 1936. Geographical data for reporting periods is complete.",
  "COPA": "Comics on Parade submitted data to the ABC during the year 1939. In 1940 it became part of the United Feature Comic Group.",
  "CRCO": "Crime Confessions first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1940 and submitted through the end of 1941. All circulation was reported as single copy sales.",
  "CRDE": "Crime Detective first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1939 and submitted through the end of 1941. All circulation was reported as single copy sales.",
  "CUDI": "Cupid’s Diary submitted individual issue circulation data to the ABC in the Dell Women’s Group reports from 1926-1927 and again between July 1929 and December 1930. No geographical breakdown was submitted for 1926 and 1927. The geographical breakdown for July-December 1929 represents the entire Dell Women’s Group, but the data from 1930 reflects the circulation of Cupid’s Diary alone.",
  "DEDE": "The Dell Detective Group first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1937 and submitted consistently through June 1946. All circulation through June 1939 was reported as single copy sales. For one reporting period (July-December 1938), geographical data for Inside Detective and Front Page Detective were separated, though they have been combined here. Both titles included in this group would appear in individual reports in the ABC beginning in 1953.",
  "DECO": "Dell Comic Group first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1937. It switched to the title Dell Super Comic Group for January-June 1939, switched back to Dell Comic Group in the following period, then settled on Dell Super Comic Group from January 1940 through its final reporting in June 1942. Dell Super Comic Group reports from 1940 separated geographical breakdowns by publisher (repurposing the form’s columns); those have been combined here into a single figure, even in the case of July-December 1940, when they forgot to retitle the columns but all evidence suggests this was the case.",
  "DETCO": "The Detective Comics Group first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1939 and submitted through the end of 1943. All circulation was reported as single copy sales. The titles included here were also included in the National Comics Group in the July-December 1943 report and folded into the National Comics Group in 1944.",
  "DEWO": "The Dell Women’s Group submitted reports under this title to the ABC beginning in the period July-December 1929, but this initial report featured breakdowns of individual titles for both issue and geographical circulation. Many of these titles also had individual circulation data submitted under reports titled Dell Publications beginning in 1926. The only data that combined multiple titles in the Dell Women’s Group was submitted from January-December 1930. All geographical data was claimed as single copy sales.",
  "DOAC": "The Double Action Group submitted data to the ABC for a single reporting period, July-December 1939. Its January-June report was marked “Statement Not Received.” All circulation was reported as single copy sales.",
  "DRWO": "Dream World first submitted reports to the ABC for the period July-December 1924, and it continued to submit under this title consistently through June 1934. Its title changed to Love and Romance with the July-December 1934 report, and it submitted under the new title through the end of 1938.",
  "DYDE": "Dynamic Detective submitted data to the ABC for a single reporting period: January-June 1938.",
  "EVER": "Everybody’s (also called Everybody’s Magazine) first submitted reports to the ABC for the period January-June 1919 and continued to submit circulation data consistently through its final issue, March 1929. Before 1924, the magazine typically submitted geographical breakdowns of subscription sales only (with one exception: July-December 1920).",
  "FECO": "Feature Comics first submitted data to the ABC (under the title Feature Funnies) for the period July-December 1938 and then submitted (under Feature Comics) through June 1940.",
  "FLAC": "Flying Aces first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1934 and submitted through June 1946. At the beginning of 1945 the report title changed to Flying Age Including Flying Aces. The report for the period July-December 1936 was stamped “Statement Not Received.”",
  "FOCO": "Fox Comic Group first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1940 and submitted through the end of 1941. All circulation was reported as single copy sales.",
  "FRON": "Frontier first submitted reports to the ABC for the period January-June 1925. Through the end of 1925, it submitted individual reports, but beginning in 1926 it submitted circulation data as part of the Short Stories and Frontier combination. These reports featured individual issue circulation for Frontier, but combined geographical circulation with Short Stories. Before 1928 geographical breakdowns represent only subscription sales.",
  "GUDE": "Guide Detective Unit first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1941 and continued to submit through the end of 1943. Beginning in 1944, Official Detective Stories, previously included in this group, reported independently.",
  "HEAR": "Heart’s International (reported also under the titles Hearst’s and merely Hearst) first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1919, and submitted regularly through 1925, when it was combined with Cosmopolitan. Geographical data is complete, with the exception of the period January-June 1925, when the magazine submitted issue circulation data for the final two issues before the merger, with no accompanying geographical data.",
  "HIT": "Hit! first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1946 and submitted through the end of 1947. All circulation was reported as single copy sales.",
  "KEN": "Ken submitted data to the ABC for a single reporting period, January-June 1939.",
  "LAFF": "Laff first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1946 and continued to submit reports through December 1947. The January-June 1948 report was not included. The ABC indicated that this report’s release was delayed because of non-compliance to the bylaws and rules of the ABC.",
  "LIFE": "The original version of Life first submitted reports to the ABC in 1919. No circulation figures are available for July-December 1936 because the magazine was not a member of the ABC at that time. In 1936, Henry R. Luce bought Life and launched a new version of the magazine on November 23. ABC reports for this version of Life began in January 1937. Circulation figures are not available for July 1928-June 1929, January-June 1933, July-December 1969, and July-December 1972 because the magazine’s statements were not received in time to be included in ABC reports. No geographic data was reported for July-December 1946. The February 19, 1920 report indicates a dip in circulation because of a paper shortage. In December 1965, 1966, and 1967, the last two issues of the year were combined into one. In July and August 1970, some former subscribers to the defunct Saturday Evening Post chose to receive copies of Life as an option to finish out their paid subscriptions for the Post.",
  "LOARO": "Love and Romance first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1934 and submitted through the end of 1938.",
  "LOOK": "Look first submitted reports to the ABC when it was founded in 1937 and continued until the magazine closed in October 1971. Circulation figures are not available for January-June 1970 because the magazine’s statement was not received in time to be included in the ABC report.",
  "METR": "Metropolitan first submitted data to the ABC under the title Metropolitan Magazine in the period January-June 1919. With one exception (July-December 1922, when its report did not appear in the microfilm held at the AAM), it submitted complete data regularly through June 1925. Its final two reports were submitted under its new title Fiction Lovers.",
  "MIMO": "Mickey Mouse Magazine first submitted reports to the ABC for the period January-June 1937 and submitted through June 1939.",
  "MOSH": "Movie Show first submitted reports to the ABC for the period January-June 1943 and submitted through September 1948.",
  "MUMA": "Munsey’s Magazine first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1919 and submitted regularly through the end of 1925, when it joined Argosy-All Story Weekly and Flynn’s in the Munsey Combination. During its individual membership in the ABC, it submitted geographical breakdowns for subscription sales only.",
  "NWST": "North West Stories (sometimes rendered as North-West Stories) first submitted individual circulation data to the ABC as part of the Fiction House Group in the period January-June 1926. It continued to submit issue data separately with this group through the end of 1928, after which its circulation was folded into the Fiction House Group total. Geographical data here is for the entire Fiction House Group, and before 1928 only subscription sales were included in geographical breakdowns.",
  "RAAG": "Radio Age first submitted reports for the January-June 1924 time period and submitted regularly through June 1926. The ABC reported that statements for July-December 1927 and January-June 1928 were not received.",
  "ROMO": "Romantic Movie Stories first submitted reports to the ABC for the period January-June 1935 and submitted reports until December 1936.",
  "ROST": "Romantic Story first submitted reports to the ABC for the period January-June 1935 and submitted reports until December 1943. The magazine originally was titled Romantic Stories, which changed to Romantic Magazine between October 1937 and June 1938. The title Romantic Story was used from July 1938 until December 1943.",
  "SCIN": "Science and Invention submitted reports to the ABC under its previous title Electrical Experimenter from January 1919-June 1920 and under Science and Invention after that. It submitted circulation information regularly through June 1931, though reports from July 1927-June 1928 were marked “Temporary Suspension of Service.” Before 1925 geographical breakdowns include only subscription sales.",
  "SCRI": "Script submitted data to the ABC under the title Rob Wagner’s Script from January 1932-June 1936 and under the simplified title Script from July 1935-June 1942. With one exception (the period June-December 1936), Script submitted geographical breakdowns of subscription sales only. Spikes in circulation in late 1934 were due to bulk sales to a California hotel as part of a promotion.",
  "SENS": "Sensation submitted reports to the ABC in 1943. May and June 1943 were combined into one issue labeled “Summer.” The magazine suspended publishing in July and August 1943 to save paper.",
  "SIR": "Sir! submitted reports to the ABC in September and November 1946 and February and March 1947. The ABC noted that no issues were published July-December 1947. For January-June 1948, ABC reported that data release was delayed because of non-compliance with the ABC’s bylaws and rules.",
  "SKRI": "Sky Riders submitted data to the ABC as part of the Dell Men’s Group for the period July-December 1929. Geographical breakdowns here are for the entire group. After this period, its circulation data was folded into the Dell Fiction Group.",
  "SNST": "Snappy Stories initially reported as part of a group (with Live Stories and Droll Stories - see Snappy Stories Group), but it first submitted individual reports to the ABC for the period January-June 1926. It continued to submit through the end of 1927. Geographical breakdowns include subscription sales only.",
  "SPFI": "Speed Fiction Group first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1945 and submitted through the end of 1946. Reports in both 1947 volumes were marked “Statement Not Received.” All circulation was reported as single copy sales.",
  "SWST": "Sweetheart Stories first submitted data to the ABC as part of the Dell Fiction Group report for the period January-June 1926. It submitted circulation information as part of this group (with no geographical breakdowns) through the end of 1927, then submitted with the Dell Women’s Group from July 1929-December 1930. From July 1934 through December 1939 Sweetheart Stories submitted individual reports. Data from the period July-December 1929 features the combined geographical breakdown of the entire Dell Women’s Group, but other geographical breakdowns are for this title alone.",
  "TEPU": "The Teck Publications Fiction Combination (consisting of Amazing Stories and Wild West Stories) first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1935 and submitted through June 1937. Beginning in mid-1936 it reported circulation for its titles individual and in the aggregate. Data for Amazing Stories is also available under that title.",
  "TITO": "Tip Top Comics first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1937 and submitted through the end of 1939.",
  "TRIX": "Triple-X first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1924 and submitted through the end of 1925.",
  "TRMA": "Marriage Stories (initially known as True Marriage Stories) submitted issue circulation data to the ABC as part of the Dell Fiction Group from 1926-1927 (with no geographical breakdowns) and as part of the Dell Women’s Group for the period July-December 1929, before it was folded into that Group’s aggregate circulation totals in 1930. The only geographical breakdowns (for the period July-December 1929) represent the entire Dell Women’s Group.",
  "VIDE": "Vital Detective Cases first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1946 and continued to submit figures through January 1948.",
  "VOGU": "Vogue first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1919 and submitted consistently through the end of 1972. After its absorption of Vanity Fair, reports beginning in 1937 were titled Vogue Incorporating Vanity Fair.",
  "WABI": "War Birds submitted submitted individual issue circulation as part of the Dell Men’s Group for periods July-December 1929 and July-December 1930. Geographical breakdowns for 1929 include the entire Dell Men’s Group, while those for 1930 feature circulation for War Birds only. In between these dates, War Birds circulation is folded into the Dell Fiction Group.",
  "WANO": "War Novels submitted individual issue circulation data to the ABC as part of the Dell Men’s Group for the periods July-December 1929 and July-December 1930. Relevant geographical data was only submitted for the 1929 report and represents the entire group. Between these reports, circulation information for War Novels was folded in to the Dell Fiction Group.",
  "WAST": "War Stories submitted individual issue circulation data to the ABC as part of the Dell Men’s Group from July 1929 through June 1930. Geographical breakdowns for 1929 include the entire Group, while those from 1930 are for War Stories only.",
  "WERO": "Western Romances submitted data as part of the Dell Men’s Group for the period July 1929-June 1930. Geographical breakdowns--available for 1929 only--represent the entire Group.",
  "WETA": "Weird Tales first submitted individual issue circulation data to the ABC for the period January-June 1939 as part of a group with Short Stories. It submitted data consistently through the end of 1940 (January issue circulation was reported with the prior year). After this, most of its reports through the final submission (December 1951) were marked “Statement Not Received,” though a few stray reports were submitted during this time (July-December 1942, July-December 1943, July-December 1944, and July-December 1950). All geographical breakdowns represent the entire circulation of the Short Stories - Weird Tales combination.",
  "YOMA": "The C.H. Young Publishing Group first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1922 under the title Young’s Magazine and Breezy Stories, and it continued to submit through the end of 1933, when these two magazines were merged and reported under the title Breezy Stories. From July 1923 through June 1927 this group also included the title Droll Stories. Prior to 1928 no geographical breakdowns were reported. The geographical breakdown for the period July-December 1933 was tied to an issue of the merged magazine, so that data does not appear here, but with Breezy Stories.",
  "EBON": "Ebony first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1947 and continued to submit through the end of 1972, with a number of interruptions. Reports from July-December 1948 and from July 1953-June 1955 were marked “Statement Not Received”; the report from January-June 1952 was marked “Statement in Correspondence”; and reports from July 1955-June 1956, July 1960-June 1961, and January-June 1966 were stamped “Release Delayed Because of Non-compliance with Rules and Bylaws of the Bureau.”",
  "NATI": "The Nation submitted data to the ABC regularly from January 1919 through the end of 1952. Circulation was disrupted by the New York printers’ strike in 1919.",
  "PHCU": "Physical Culture (also reported as Physical Culture Magazine) submitted data beginning with the period January-June 1919 and submitted through the end of 1941, with one brief hiatus. Reports from July-December 1920 and January-June 1921 do not appear in the AAM archives. Additionally, issue circulation figures from January-June 1923 are obscured in the AAM microfilm.",
  "RARO": "Ranch Romances first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1925. It submitted individual reports for the period July-December 1925 and January-June 1927, but was included in in the Clayton Magazines (Bimonthly) Group from July 1927 through the end of 1930. It was included in the Clayton Magazines Group in 1926 and again in 1931 and 1932. It submitted a joint report with Black Mask from July 1934-July 1940, for which it submitted individual issue circulation numbers but combined geographical circulation data. From July 1940-June 1950 it submitted individual reports. Reports from 1925 and 1927 include no geographical breakdowns.",
  "COSM": "Cosmopolitan first submitted reports to the ABC for January-June 1919. After its purchase by the Hearst Corporation, it was merged with Heart’s International, and reports were submitted under the title Hearst’s International-Cosmopolitan (March 1925-December 1943) and Hearst’s International combined with Cosmopolitan (January 1944-June 1952). In July 1953, the name reverted to simply Cosmopolitan, and the magazine continued to submit reports through December 1972. Circulation of Hearst’s International through early 1925 is available under that title.",
  "ESQU": "Esquire first submitted circulation data to the ABC for the period January-June 1934, and it submitted consistently through the end of 1972.",
  "MACO": "Marvel Comic Group first submitted circulation data to the ABC for the period July-December 1946. It submitted under this title through the June 1958, after which it submitted its aggregate report under the title “Marvel Comic Group (Yellow & Red Combined)” in addition to two smaller subdivisions (Yellow and Red Groups). It submitted in this form through June 1967, returning after that to the simpler Marvel Comic Group through the end of 1972. It often submitted reports for two-month periods (i.e., May-June); these are represented in our data by the first month listed. The report from January-June 1957 was marked “Release Delayed Because of Non-Compliance With Rules and Bylaws of the Bureau,” and the report for July-December 1969 (which included the June-July data) was stamped “Statement Not Released in Time to be included in this Book.” Because of the sheer volume of individual titles and publishers included in this group, these do not appear in our data.",
  "MCCL": "McClure’s (which also submitted reports under the title McClure’s Magazine) first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1919 and continued to submit through December 1923. The report covering July-December 1921 was missing from the microfilm, and a report from January-June 1924 was stamped “Statement in Correspondence.” It then disappeared from the ABC Blue Books and reappeared with reports covering the period July 1927-June 1929. Geographical breakdowns from the period 1919-1923 included only subscription sales.",
  "NACO": "National Comics Group first submitted reports for the period July-December 1943 under the name “National Comics Group (Monthly Unit)” and submitted under this title through June 1947, though the January-June 1947 report featured no data and was marked “Statement in Correspondence.” From July 1947 through December 1969, it submitted under the title “National Comic Group - Combined Red and Blue Monthly Units,” an aggregation of two subdivided units. From January 1970 through the end of 1972, it added another unit and submitted reports under the title “National Comics Group - Combined Red, Blue and Teen Romance Monthly Unit.” Geographical data for the second half of 1971 and 1972 were “projected” totals based on the reports submitted in the first half of each of those years. Because of the sheer volume of individual titles included in this group, these do not appear in our data.",
  "WOHO": "Woman’s Home Companion first submitted reports to the ABC in 1919 and continued to submit through 1957. Circulation figures are not available for January-June 1925 because the magazine’s statement was not received in time to be included in the ABC report. The geographical data from July-December 1952 were taken from a very poor microfilm and may have minor errors.",
  "NEWS": "Newsweek first submitted reports to the ABC in 1934. No circulation data was reported between December 26, 1936 and February 27, 1937. This is most likely due to a change in publisher. It continued to submit consistently through 1972.",
  "TRCOM": "True Comics first submitted reports to the ABC for the period January-June 1943. It submitted through the end of 1948.",
  "REDB": "Redbook first submitted reports to the ABC (as Red Book Magazine) for the period January-June 1919. In 1929, it became Redbook Magazine, and it submitted consistently through 1972.",
  "TIME": "Time first submitted reports to the ABC in 1924, and it submitted consistently through 1972.",
  "BEHO": "Better Homes and Gardens first submitted reports to the ABC under the title Fruit, Garden and Home for the period January-June 1923. In 1924, the magazine changed its name to Better Homes & Gardens. It continued to submit consistently through 1972.",
  "CLIM": "Climax first submitted reports to the ABC for the period January-June 1958 and submitted through the end of 1963.",
  "CONF": "Confidential first submitted reports to the ABC for the period July-December 1955 and submitted through June 1959.",
  "FAFU": "Famous Funnies first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1936 and continued to submit through the end of 1942.",
  "FOME": "For Men Only first submitted submitted data for the period January-June 1956, and it continued to submit through the end of 1972. The report from January-June 1957 was stamped “Release delayed because of non-compliance with rules and bylaws of the Bureau.”",
  "FORT": "Fortune first submitted reports to the ABC in 1931 and submitted through 1972. Fortune tended to be published on a monthly basis, but there were also mid-month issues published in June 1967, September 1967, June 1968, September 1968, May 1969, and August 1969. For the April 1944 issue, there is a curious typing error. The value that appears is 181,4023. Circulation figures in the first half of 1944 were in the 176,913-184,829 range, so 181,402 was the figure that was included in the dataset.",
  "JET": "Jet first submitted reports to the ABC for the period January-June 1953, and it submitted with some interruptions through the end of 1972. Reports from January 1954 through June 1956 were marked “Statement Not Received”; reports from July 1960-June 1961 and January-June 1966 were stamped “Release Delayed because of Non-Compliance With Rules and Bylaws of the Bureau”; and reports from January-June 1969 were labeled “Statement Not Releasef In Time to be Included in this Book.”",
  "LISN": "The unit we have called the “Snappy Stories Group” first submitted combined reports for the period July-December 1922 for two titles: Live Stories and Snappy Stories. It continued to submit these two titles together through June 1925, and for its final reporting period of July-December 1925 it submitted data for three titles: Snappy Stories, Wit of the World, and Live Stories. Bimonthly issues were labeled 1st and 2nd issues of the month, with no specific date. Snappy Stories submitted reports independently beginning in 1926.",
  "MCCA": "McCall’s first submitted reports to the ABC for the period January-June 1919 under the title McCall’s Magazine. It submitted through June 1958 under this title, and beginning in July 1958 it submitted under the title McCall’s through the end of 1972. The report from January-June 1970 was marked “Statement Not Released in Time to Be Included in this Book.”",
  "SPIL": "Sports Illustrated first submitted reports to the ABC for the period July-December 1954 and continued to submit consistently through the end of 1972.",
  "TETA": "Telling Tales first submitted reports to the ABC for the period July-December 1922 and submitted through the end of 1925. Its reports featured no state-by-state breakdowns, only totals for Mail Subscribers and Newsdealers.",
  "TAN": "Tan first submitted data under the title Tan Confessions for the period July-December 1951. The magazine’s title changed to Tan with the September 1952 issue, and it began reporting under this title for the July-December 1952 period. It submitted data through June 1971 with a number of interruptions. The report from January-June 1952 was marked “Statement in Correspondence”; reports from July 1953-June 1955 were marked “Statement Not Received”; reports from July 1955-June 1956, July 1960-June 1961, and January-June 1966 were stamped “Release Delayed Because of Non-Compliance With Rules and Bylaws of the Bureau”; and the report from January-June 1969 was marked “Statement Not Released in Time to Be Included in this Book.”",
  "STAG": "Stag first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1952, and it submitted regularly through 1972, with two exceptions. Its January-June 1957 report was marked “Release delayed because of non-compliance with rules and bylaws of the Bureau,” and its January-June 1970 report was marked “Statement Not Released in Time to be Included in this Book.”",
  "NAGE": "National Geographic Magazine first submitted reports to the ABC in 1919. Single issue circulation figures are not available for July-December 1919 because they did not appear in the ABC’s microfilm archive; however, state-by-state figures (based on the December 1919 issue) are available for this time period. The magazine submitted consistently through 1972, though the report for January-June 1934 was marked “Statement in Correspondence,” and the report from January-June 1970 was marked “Statement not released in time to be included in this book.”",
  "JETR": "The Jewish Tribune first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1921, and it submitted consistently through the end of 1930. The report from January-June 19341 was marked “Statement Not Received.”",
  "FORB": "Forbes first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1922 under the title Forbes Magazine. With one exception (July-December 1925, marked “Statement in Correspondence”), it submitted consistently under this title through the end of 1946. In 1947 it began submitting under the title Forbes and continued to submit consistently through 1972.",
  "DOBE": "Down Beat first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1945. It submitted through June 1950 and left the ABC, returning for the period July-December 1952. It then submitted continually through the end of 1955, leaving the ABC again, only to return for the January-June 1958 period. Upon this return, it submitted consistently through 1972.",
  "COLO": "Color first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1950. It only submitted a handful of reports before leaving the ABC at the end of 1955. Reports submitted include July-December 1951, July-December 1952, and January-June 1955. Missing reports between 1950 and 1952 and for the period July-December 1953 were marked “Release delayed because of noncompliance with Rules and Bylaws of the Bureau.” The report for January-June 1953 was stamped “Statement in Correspondence,” and the missing reports from 1954-1955 were marked “Statement Not Received.”",
  "BRTH": "Bronze Thrills first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1955 and continued to submit--with a number of interruptions--through 1972. Reports from January-June 1957, January-December 1963, and January-June 1966 were marked “Statement Not Received”; reports from July-December 1964, January-December 1965, and July-December 1966 were labeled “Statement in Correspondence”; and reports from July-December 1968 and July-December 1969 were stamped “Statement Not Released in Time to be Included in this Book.”",
  "BNBR": "B’nai B’rith Magazine first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1925 (though an initial report for late 1924 was marked “Statement Not Received.”). It submitted relatively consistently through the end of 1937. Reports from July-December 1929 and January-June 1938 were marked “Statement in Correspondence.”",
  "ARCH": "Archie Comics first submitted data. to the ABC for the period July-December 1946, and it submitted data for the following reporting period (January-June 1947). The following two reports were marked “Statement in Correspondence” and “Statement Not Received,” respectively. This title became a part of the Archie Comic Group in 1947.",
  "ARCG": "The Archie Comic Group first submitted reports to the ABC for the period July-December 1947, though its initial report was stamped “Statement in Correspondence.” In continued to submit consistently through 1972, though one other report (January-June 1950) was also stamped “Statement in Correspondence.”",
  "FIST": "Field and Stream first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1919 and submitted consistently through the end of 1972.",
  "JIVE": "Jive first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1955. It continued to submit through the end of 1972, with a number of interruptions. Reports for January-June 1957, January-December 1963, and January-June 1966 were marked “Statement Not Received.” Reports for July-December 1957, July 1964-December 1965, and July-December 1966 were marked “Statement in Correspondence.” And reports from July-December 1968, July-December 1969, and July-December 1970 were marked “Statement Not Released In Time To Be Included In This Book.”",
  "MANS": "Man’s Magazine first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1956 and submitted consistently through the end of 1971. Reports from July 1955-June 1956 were marked “Statement Not Received,” and those from January-December 1972 were marked “Statement not released in time to be included in this book.”",
  "OUWO": "Our World first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1947 and submitted through June 1955 with one interruption. Reports from July 1953 through June 1954 were marked “Release delayed because of non-compliance with Rules and Bylaws of the Bureau.”",
  "REDI": "Reader’s Digest first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1955 and submitted consistently through the end of 1972.",
  "RERE": "Review of Reviews first submitted data under the title American Review of Reviews to the ABC for the period January-June 1919 and submitted under this title until June 1928. In the July-December 1919 report and in all reports beginning in July 1928 the title was reported as Review of Reviews. It submitted consistently through June 1937.",
  "SAGA": "Saga first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1951, and it submitted consistently through the end of 1971. Reports for both 1972 reporting periods were marked “Statement Not Released In Time to Be Included in This Book.”",
  "SCAM": "Scientific American first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1919. On October 20, 1921, Scientific American (weekly version) and Scientific American Monthly were combined into one monthly publication. The first issue of the new Scientific American was published on October 20, 1921, and dated November 1921, and the magazine submitted data through the end of 1972. The report for July-December 1931 was marked “Statement Not Received.” Reports before 1928 include geographical breakdowns for mail subscriptions only.",
  "SCRO": "Screen Romances first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1929 and continued to submit through the end of 1947.",
  "WORE": "World Report submitted data to the ABC from the beginning of 1947 until January 6, 1948. On January 13, 1948, World Report consolidated with United States News to become US News & World Report.",
  "HABA": "Harper’s Bazaar first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1925 and submitted consistently through the end of 1972. From 1925-1929, it submitted under the title Harper’s Bazar, and from 1948-1966 it submitted under the title Harper's Bazaar Incorporating Junior Bazaar.",
  "TRST": "True Story first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1921 and continued to submit through the end of 1972. Reports from July-December 1969, January-June 1970, and January-June 1972 were marked “Statement not released in time to be included in this book.”",
  "TOMA": "Tower Magazines first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1931 and submitted consistently through June 1935. The report from July-December 1935 was marked “Statement Not Received.”",
  "UNFE": "United Feature Comic Group first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1940 and submitted through the end of 1954. The report from January-June 1950 was marked “Statement Not Received.” After June 1940, all circulation was reported as newsstand sales.",
  "FIFU": "Film Fun first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1924 and submitted through the end of 1938. This title did not appear in the July-December 1926 and January-June 1927 Blue Books, and the report from January-June 1928 was marked “Statement Not Received.” Reports before July 1928 included geographical breakdowns for mail subscriptions only.",
  "LAHO": "Ladies’ Home Journal first submitted data to the ABC in 1924 and submitted consistently through the end of 1972. In 1962 and 1963, July and August issues were combined into one and labeled “Summer.” In 1962 and 1963, January and February issues were combined into one and labeled “Winter.” The magazine’s statement with circulation figures for January-June 1970 was not released in time to be included in the ABC’s report.",
  "OPIN": "Opinion - A Journal of Jewish Life and Letters first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1934. It submitted data through the end of 1947, with a few exceptions. The reports for January-June 1943 and January-June 1947 were marked “Release delayed because of non-compliance with Bylaws and Rules.” Reports for 1948 were also marked “Release delayed because of non-compliance with Bylaws and Rules,” and one final report (January-June 1949) was marked “Statement Not Received.” For its final report (July-December 1947) the magazine submitted under the abbreviated title Opinion. This magazine only submitted geographical breakdowns for mail subscriptions.",
  "PIC": "Pic first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1938 and submitted consistently through the end of 1948.",
  "SARE": "The Saturday Review first submitted reports under the title The Saturday Review or Literature for the period July-December 1940. It submitted under this title through the end of 1951. Beginning in 1952, it submitted consistently under the briefer title through 1972. The July-December 1972 report was marked “Statement Not Released in Time to Be Included in this Book.”",
  "SEPI": "Sepia first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1955 and it submitted through the end of 1972. Reports for January-June 1957, January-June 1963, July-December 1963, and January-June 1966 were marked “Statement Not Received.” Reports for July-December 1964, January-June 1965, July-December 1965, and July-December 1966 were marked “Statement in Correspondence.” And reports for July-December 1968 and July-December 1969 were marked “Statement Not Released in Time to be Included in this Book.”",
  "STDE": "Startling Detective first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1946 and submitted through June 1947.",
  "THCO": "The Thrilling Comics Group first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1944 and submitted consistently through the end of 1948.",
  "WHCO": "Whiz Comics first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1944 and submitted consistently through the end of 1946.",
  "GLAM": "Glamour first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1939 and submitted consistently through 1972. From July 1939 through June 1941 it submitted under the title Glamour of Hollywood, after which it used the shorter title Glamour, with one brief exception. Between November 1959 and December 1961, it assumed the title Glamour Incorporating Charm, after the publication Charm was discontinued. 19,015 Charm subscriptions were transferred to Glamour starting with the November issue.",
  "LEGL": "The Lev Gleason Comic Group first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1943 under the name Magazine House Group. It submitted under this title through October 1945, after which it submitted under the name Lev Gleason through 1955. These reports often included December and June reports with the following reporting period. Reports for Jaunuary-June 1945 and July-December 1955 were marked “Statement Not Received.” All circulation was reported as single copy sales.",
  "MADEM": "Mademoiselle first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1936 and submitted consistently through 1972. The June and July 1937 issues were combined into one June-July issue and published on June 15, 1937.",
  "MALE": "Male first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1952 and submitted through 1972. The report for the period January-June 1952 refers readers to the Stag Group, which included Male, and the report for the period January-June 1957 was marked “Release delayed because of non-compliance with rules and bylaws of the Bureau.” All circulation was reported as single copy sales.",
  "MEN": "Men first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1953 and submitted through 1972. The report for January-June was marked “Release Delayed Because of Non-Compliance With Rules and Bylaws of the Bureau,” and the report for January-June 1970 was marked “Statement Not Released In Time To Be Included In This Book.” All circulation was reported as single copy sales.",
  "PIPL": "Picture Play first submitted data to the ABC under the title Picture Play Magazine for the period January-June 1920. It changed to the shorter Picture Play in the July-December 1923 report and used this through its final report in 1940, with one brief exception. The reports from July 1938-June 1939 used the title Street & Smith’s Picture Play. In 1926 and 1927 geographical breakdowns for single copy sales were not reported.",
  "SOJU": "Social Justice first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1938 and submitted through July 1940. The report from July-December 1939 was marked “Statement in Correspondence.”",
  "TRCO": "True Confessions first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1924. The report for July-December 1925 was marked “Statement Not Received,” and the magazine was not in the ABC from January 1926 through June 1932. It reappeared in the ABC Blue Books in the July-December 1932 volume and submitted through 1972 with on additional interruption: January-June 1970, which was marked “Statement Not Released in Time to Be Included in this Book.” Beginning in 1964, all geographical circulation was reported as single copy sales.",
  "HOLL": "Hollywood first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1928 and submitted consistently through the March 1943, at which point it was absorbed by Motion Picture.",
  "REDE": "Read Detective first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1931 and submitted through the end of 1941 with one interruption. The report for July-December 1932 was marked “Statement Not Received. Publication Changed Ownership.” From January 1937 through June 1941, the magazine submitted under the title Real Detective Magazine.",
  "FACO": "Fawcett Comics Group first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1943 under the title Fawcett Comic Group - Red and Blue Unit. It submitted under this title through the end of 1946, after which it used the shorter Fawcett Comics Group and submitted through the end of 1952. All circulation was reported as single copy sales. Figures for July-December 1945 were derived by combining figures from individual reports for Red Unit and Blue Unit, as no combined report was submitted for that period.",
  "MOMIR": "Movie Mirror (1956) was the second magazine with this title to submit data to the ABC. Founded in 1956, it first submitted data to the period January-June 1958. It submitted consistently through 1972 with one exception: the January-June 1959 report, which was marked “Statement in Correspondence.” All circulation was reported as single copy sales.",
  "AITR": "Air Trails first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1936 under the title Bill Barnes Air Trails. It submitted under this title through January 1937, shortening the title to Air Trails in February 1937 and using this for most of its membership. From August 1942 through December 1950 it submitted under the title Air Trails Pictorial, and from January 1954 through June 1955 it submitted under the title Air Trails Hobbies for Young Men.",
  "MOMI": "Movie Mirror (1934), the first magazine that was submitted under this title, first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1934 and continued to submit through the end of 1940, after which it was combined with Photoplay.",
  "PIRE": "Pictorial Review first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1919 and submitted through the end of 1938. It submitted two reports for January-June 1937. The first was titled Pictorial Review, while the second (covering May and June) was titled Pictorial Review Combined with Delineator. The magazine submitted under this title through the end of 1938.",
  "GOHO": "Good Housekeeping first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1919 and submitted through the end of 1972. Some numbers on the geographic report for July-December 1920 were very difficult to read because of a poor quality microfilm scan. Numbers for Middle and Western States were reconstructed as best as possible based on the available information.",
  "TVGU": "TV Guide submitted a number of different reports during its membership in the ABC. Some reports were for the “franchise edition,” while others were regionally specific. For our data, we have used the magazine’s “consolidated” report, which was first submitted to the ABC for the period July-December 1950. The report for July-December 1955 was marked “Statement in Correspondence.”",
  "WORWO": "The World’s Work first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1919 and submitted through June 1932. Geographical data before 1928 features a state-by-state breakdown of subscription sales only.",
  "WOWO": "Woman’s World first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1919 and submitted consistently through June 1940. Geographical data before July 1929 features a state-by-state breakdown of subscription sales only. This magazine has no affiliation or connection to the Woman’s World weekly magazine that launched in 1981.",
  "YOCO": "The Youth’s Companion first submitted reports to the ABC for the period July-December 1919 and submitted consistently through the end of 1929. Geographical data before 1929 features a state-by-state breakdown of subscription sales only.",
  "SCLI": "Screen Life first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1940 and submitted through the end of 1941.",
  "USNE": "United States News first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1935. United States News consolidated with World Report starting on January 13, 1948 to become U.S. News and World Report. Geographical data before 1946 features a state-by-state breakdown of subscription sales only.",
  "FASC": "Fawcett Screen Unit first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1943 and submitted consistently through July 1951. No geographical data was submitted with its final report, which featured just a single month of reported circulation.",
  "HUSC": "Hunter Screen Unit first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1945 and submitted through September 1948.",
  "USWR": "U.S. News & World Report first submitted data to the ABC for the January-June 1948, after the titles United States News and World Report were combined into a single publication. It submitted consistently through the end of 1972.",
  "TRRO": "True Romance first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1924 under the title True Romances. Its title changed to True Romance at the beginning of 1947, and it submitted through 1972, with minor interruptions. Reports from July 1969 through June 1970 and the report from January-June 1972 were marked “Statement Not Released in Time To Be Included in this Book.”",
  "ARGO": "Argosy first submitted individual data to the ABC for the period July-December 1943. It has previously appeared in various combinations and groups (Argosy-All-Story, Munsey Combination, and Popular Publications. It submitted consistently through 1972.",
  "CHAR": "Charm first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1941 and submitted consistently through October 1949.",
  "CLIC": "Click first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1938 and submitted consistently through January 1945. In 1943 and 1944, Click used March as the sample issue for both January-June and July-December geodata reports. Circulation for its final issue was included in the July-December 1944 report.",
  "FOST": "Forest and Stream first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1919 and submitted through the end of 1929. Its January-June 1930 report was marked “Statement not received,” and the magazine merged with Field and Stream in July 1930. Prior to July 1928, geographical breakdown was submitted for subscription sales only.",
  "MADET": "Master Detective first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1932 and submitted through 1972. No circulation information was reported between September 1950 and August 1952. Reports from July-December 1969 and January-June 1970 were marked “Statement Not Released in Time To Be Included in This Book.”",
  "PHOT": "Photoplay first submitted data to the ABC (under the title Photoplay Magazine) for the period January-June 1919. It submitted under this title through the end of 1932, shortening the title to Photoplay in 1933. From January 1941 through June 1944 it submitted under the title Photoplay-Movie Mirror after its combination with Movie Mirror. It returned to the briefer Photoplay and submitted through 1972. Reports from July-December 1969 and January-June 1972 were marked “Statement not released in time to be included in this book.” Reports from 1919 featured geographical breakdowns of subscription sales only.",
  "NERE": "The New Republic first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1938. It submitted in two separate periods, from 1938 through 1951 and then, when it presumably rejoined the ABC, from 1966 through 1972. Reports from January-June and July-December 1970 were marked “Statement Not Released in Time to Be Included in this Book.”",
  "ROLST": "Rolling Stone first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1971 and submitted through 1972. The report for January-June 1971 was only found in the AAM microfilm.",
  "SEE": "See first submitted data to the ABC for the period June-December 1944 and submitted through 1957. The January-June 1958 report was marked “Statement Not Received.” All circulation was reported as single copy sales.",
  "SSCO": "Street & Smith Comics Group first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1942 and submitted through June 1946. Prior to July 1944, groups were reported quarterly.",
  "SEVE": "Seventeen first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1944 and submitted consistently through 1972. All circulation for the period July-December 1944 was reported as single copy sales.",
  "UNCO": "Uncensored Confessions first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1956 and submitted through January 1961. The report for July-December 1956 was missing from the AAM microfilm, and circulation for the final issue (January 1961) was included on the July-December 1960 report. All circulation was reported as single copy sales.",
  "TRDE": "True Detective first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1924. From July 1924 through June 1941 it submitted under the title True Detective Mysteries, submitting under the abbreviated True Detective through 1972. The report for July-December 1964 was missing from the ABC Blue Book, and reports for July-December 1969 and January-June 1970 were marked, “Statement not released in time to be included in this book.”",
  "SPUR": "The Spur first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1937 and submitted consistently through June 1940.",
  "TOWO": "Today’s Woman first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1945 and submitted consistently through June 1954.",
  "WOWE": "Woman’s Weekly first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1919 and submitted through June 1924. In geographical breakdowns, virtually all circulation was reported as subscription sales. However, the January-June 1919 report indicated that single copy sales were sold by “Boy Agents.”",
  "TRLIS": "True Life Stories submitted data to the ABC for two different periods, from January-August 1954 and from January 1957-June 1958. All circulation was reported as single copy sales.",
  "TRLID": "Tru-Life Detective Cases first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1946 and submitted through the end of 1947. Reporting was unusual in that the report for January-June 1947 included figures from the August and September issues and the report for July-December 1947 included the figure for January 1948. The final report that appeared in the Blue Books--for January-June 1948--was marked “Release delayed because of non-compliance with Bylaws and Rules of the Bureau.” All geographical data was reported as single copy sales.",
  "MOPIC": "Motion Picture Classic first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1919, and it submitted under a number of titles through February 1937. From July 1922 through June 1924 its report was submitted under the simple title Classic, and beginning in July 1931 it submitted under the title Movie Classic. In 1937 it was subsumed by Motion Picture (briefly under the title Motion Picture-Movie Classic). Two reports were submitted, one for January and February, for Movie Classic, and a second - which we have included with Motion Picture.",
  "MOPIM": "Motion Picture first submitted data to the ABC under the title Motion Picture Magazine for the period January-June 1919, and it submitted under a number of titles through 1972. It began submitting under the briefer title Motion Picture in July 1929, and between March and December of 1937 it submitted under the title Motion Picture-Movie Classic after acquiring a competitor. It submitted two reports for the period January-June 1937, one under Motion Picture and the other as Motion Picture-Movie Classic. For visualizations, we have included the second title. It reverted to Motion Picture in 1938, reported as Motion Picture combined with Hollywood for April-June 1943 and as Motion Picture and Television Magazine for August 1951 through September 1954. The July-December 1951 report contained no geographical breakdowns, and three reports (July-December 1969, January-June 1970, and January-June 1972) were marked “Statement not released in time to be included in this book.” Beginning in 1964, all circulation was reported as single copy sales.",
  "CUHI": "Current History first submitted data to the ABC under the title The New York Times Current History for the period July-December 1919. It submitted under this title through the end of 1920, shortening its title to Current History Magazine in 1921. It alternated between this title and Current History through June 1940. After subsuming the Forum, it reported under the title Current History and Forum for July-December 1940. This magazine’s final report (July-December 1940) featured geographical breakdowns tied to the individual titles (Current History and Forum) and, because of problems with consistency, was excluded from the dataset. A January-June 1941 report was marked “Membership cancelled because of change of ownership.” Reports before 1924 featured geographical breakdowns of subscription sales only.",
  "MOVI": "Movies first submitted data to the ABC under the title Movies Magazine for the period January-June 1939. Beginning in 1940 it submitted under the shorter title Movies and did so through April 1948. The report for January-June 1947 was marked “Statement in Correspondence,” and the final report noted “Discontinued after April, 1948, issue.”",
  "ASIA": "Asia first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1919. In 1919 its subtitle was Journal of the American Asiatic Association, and from January 1920 through June 1923 it submitted with the subtitle The Magazine of the Orient. It submitted under the simplified title Asia through June 1942. It then left the ABC and returned as Asia in the Americas from July 1944 through June 1946. The report from July-December 1928 was marked “Statement in Correspondence,” and a report from July-December 1946 was marked “Statement Not Received.” Circulation before 1928 submitted geographical breakdowns for subscription sales only, with two exceptions (January-June 1919 and January-June 1922).",
  "FACI": "Family Circle first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1949. It submitted through December 1957, left the ABC, and resumed its membership, submitting reports from January 1963 through 1972. All circulation was reported as single copy sales. No copy of the July-December 1968 was found in any existing sources.",
  "MOST": "Movie Story first submitted data to the ABC under the title Romantic Movie Stories for the period January-June 1935. It submitted under this title through the end of 1936, submitting under Movie Story Magazine from January 1937 through December 1947 and under Movie Story from January 1948 through July 1951. Its final report, which contained circulation for one issue only (July 1951), contained no geographical data.",
  "OFDE": "Official Detective Stories first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1935 and submitted through 1972. The report for January-June 1970 was marked “Statement Not Released In Time To Be Included In This Book.”",
  "PENT": "Penthouse first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1970 and submitted through 1972.",
  "WOME": "Women first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1937 and submitted through the end of 1938. The January-June 1939 report was marked “Statement Not Received.”",
  "VARS": "Varsity first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1948 and submitted through the end of 1950.",
  "PARE": "The Parents’ Magazine first submitted data to the ABC under the title Children, The Magazine for Parents for the period January-June 1927. It submitted under this title through June 1928, changing its title to Children, The Parents’ Magazine for the period July-December 1928, and using The Parents’ Magazine through June 1959. From July 1959 through June 1968 it used the title Parents’ Magazine & Better Homemaking and from July 1968 through the end of 1972 it used the title Parents’ Magazine & Better Family Living.",
  "GOUR": "Gourmet first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1946 and submitted through 1972. Reports for July-December 1953 and July-December 1954 were marked “Statement in Correspondence,” and the report for January-June 1970 was marked “Statement not released in time to be included in volume.”",
  "HOBE": "House Beautiful first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1919 and submitted consistently through 1972. It used the title The House Beautiful through June 1929 and submitted under the titled House Beautiful combined with Home & Field from January 1934 through June 1943. Reports for January-June 1919 and January-June 1927 included geographical breakdowns of subscription sales only.",
  "SCLA": "Screenland first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1921, and it submitted intermittently through June 1971. Its January-June 1924 statement was marked “Statement Not Received,” and reports from July 1924 through December 1926 were marked “No Statement Because of Temporary Suspension of Service.” It was reinstated in 1927, but its January-June 1928 statement was marked “No Statement Received.” Following this, it submitted consistently through December 1940. From January 1941 through 1946, it was included in the Screenland Unit. It returned to submitting on an individual basis from July 1946 through December 1948. From 1949 and 1954 it again submitted data only as part of the Screenland Unit. It returned to individual submission in January 1955 under the title Screenland Plus TV Land, using this title through June 1971. Reports from July-December 1969 and January-June 1970 were marked “Statement Not Released In Time To Be Included In This Book.” Reports for January-June and July-December 1927 featured geographical breakdowns for subscription sales only, and the January-June 1927 report included a letter explaining late submission for this “Reinstatement Statement.” Beginning in 1955, all circulation was reported as single copy sales.",
  "SCST": "The first magazine to submit under the title Screen Stars first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1944 and submitted through June 1947.",
  "SCSTA": "The second magazine to submit under the title Screen Stars, founded in 1949, first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1952, and it submitted through 1972. Around the time it had a change in ownership, it dropped out of the ABC for the period January-June 1957 and data for July-December 1957 was listed in the Screen Stars Group report. In 1958 it resumed submitting as a single title. The geographical report for the Screen Stars Group for July-December 1957 uses the September 1957 issue of Screen Stars as an example, but notes that the “figures are based on the percentage for each State and Province determined by analysis of March, 1957 group and these percentages are projected against the total for September, 1957 group.” The report for January-June 1970 was marked “Statement Not Released in Time To Be Included in This Book.” All circulation for this title was reported as single copy sales.",
  "TREX": "True Experiences first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1926 and submitted through 1972. It submitted under this title through June 1951, with one brief interruption, when it used the briefer title Experiences in the January-June 1949 report. From July 1951 through the end of 1972 it uses the title True Experience. The report from July-December 1932 was marked “Statement Not Received,” and statements from July-December 1969 and January-June 1970 were marked “Statement Not Released in Time to be Included in this Book.”",
  "LORO": "Love Romances submitted data to the ABC from January-December 1926. No geographical breakdown of circulation was submitted.",
  "HACO": "Harvey Comics Group first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1947 and submitted through 1972. Circulation was reported in two-month increments (i.e., January-February or, beginning in 1959, February-March), and we have used the first month of the two-month period for our data set. Reports for July-December 1963 and July-December 1964 were marked “Statement in Correspondence” and the report for July-December 1970 was marked “Statement Not Released in Time to be Included in this Book.” From 1948 through 1952 circulation was broken down between subscriptions and single copy sales; otherwise, all circulation was reported as single copy sales.",
  "FFHC": "The magazines we have characterized as the Famous Funnies Group first submitted a combined statement for Famous Funnies and Heroic Comics for the period January-June 1943. Heroic Comics became New Heroic Comics in January 1947, and the group submitted data through June 1950. The report for July-December 1950 was marked “Statement in Correspondence.” Statements after June 1944 reported all sales as single copy sales.",
  "HOLI": "Holiday first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1946 and submitted consistently through June 1969. Reports for July-December 1970 and January-June 1971 were also submitted, but reports for July-December 1969, January-June 1970, July-December 1971, and July-December 1972 were marked “Statement Not Released In Time To Be Included in this Volume.” No report for January-June 1972 was found in the Blue Books or in the microfilm archive.",
  "MORO": "Modern Romances first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1932 and submitted consistently through 1972.",
  "PRGR": "The Premium Group of Comics first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1945 and submitted through the end of 1948. The report for January-June 1949 was marked “Statement in Correspondence,” and the report for July-December 1949 was marked “Statement Not Received.” All circulation was reported as single copy sales.",
  "TRLO": "True Love submitted data to the ABC under a number of titles beginning with the period July-December 1924. From July 1924-June 1934, it submitted under the title Dream World; from July 1934 to December 1938, it submitted under the title Love and Romance. From January 1939 to December 1948, it submitted under the title True Love and Romance, with a number of intermittent changes (June and July 1945: True Love and Romance Stories; August-December 1945: True Love Stories; December 1948: True Love and Romance Stories). From January 1949 through June 1957, it submitted under the title True Love Stories, and from July 1957 through 1972, it submitted under True Love. It submitted data consistently, though reports from July-December 1969, January-June 1970, and January-June 1972 were marked “Statement Not Released In Time To Be Included In This Book.”",
  "COLI": "Country Life first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1922 and submitted consistently through the end of 1941, when the publication was suspended for the duration of the war. The magazine did not submit figures for November of December 1927, but from January 1938 through June 1939 it submitted under the title Country Life and The Sportsman an from July-December 1939 it used the title Country Life (Combined with Horse & Horseman and The Sportsman), after which it returned to the title Country Life. Before 1928, geographical breakdowns were submitted for subscription sales only.",
  "SCSTO": "Screen Stories first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1948 and submitted consistently through 1972.",
  "ZIDA": "Ziff-Davis Fiction Group first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1939 and submitted consistently through June 1952.",
  "HIMO": "Hillman Movie Group first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1947 and submitted consistently through December 1951.",
  "MIPI": "Mid-Week Pictorial first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1924 and submitted consistently through June 1936. The final ABC report, for July-December 1936, was marked “Release Delayed Because of Non-Compliance with By-Laws and Rules.”",
  "SCGU": "Screen Guide first submitted data to the ABC for the period July-December 1937. It continued to submit through the end of 1942 as a single title. Between January 1943 and June 1944 circulation was only reported as part of the Screen Guide-Stardom Combination and is not represented here. It resumed reporting of single title data in September 1944 and submitted through June 1951. Because of an ownership change, two reports were submitted for the period January-June 1947. One featured data from January-March (including geographical distribution for the March issue), while the other featured data from April-June (including geographical distribution for the April issue).",
  "DEMO": "The Dell Modern Group first submitted data for the period July-December 1941 under the title Modern Magazines. It submitted under this title through December 1945. From January 1946 through 1972 it submitted consistently as Dell Modern Group.",
  "TRAV": "Travel first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1925 and submitted consistently through June 1942. Generally, the magazine only submitted geographical breakdowns for mail subscriptions. It did, however, submit geographical breakdowns for single copy sales in reports for the periods January-June 1925, July-December 1925, January-June 1937, July-December 1937, January-June 1938, and from the beginning of 1939 through its final report of January-June 1942.",
  "POSC": "Popular Science Monthly first submitted data to the ABC for the period January-June 1919 and submitted consistently through the end of 1972."
}